node.text:
Do what you love. Don't listen to anyone else who tells you not to do it. You do what you want, what you love.
-
Couldn’t have imagined I’d be where I was today a decade ago. If I were to have listen to everyone else I would of never taken the leap of faith.
-
Find your passion and dedicate all your attention, focus, and energy to that one thing!
-
My last only Olympia routine. Love watching this video cause it makes me fired up to get back up there!!

node.text:
Nothing great in the world has ever been accomplished without passion.
-
When you identify your passion and align it with whatever you’re doing, a magical synergy happens that will effortlessly carry you to new heights. Work becomes enjoyable. Hours fly by. Soreness and fatigue take a backseat as you power your way to greater achievements.
-
Work extremely hard and love what you do. Yes. There’s always going to be someone more talented than you, but there's no substitute for passion. People who are passionate always work the hardest, and that sets them apart!
-
#repost @makaveli_motivation

node.text:
It isn’t something that is handed to you, you must earn that feeling.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Weight lifting is ultimately what created that feeling for me. The state of constantly working on my body, learning about training, and staying on top of my eating and sleep habits gave me gratification that I was accomplishing something every single day. ⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
By being in a state of growth on a consistent basis, it translated to my work, relationships, and overall well-being. Ultimately, that shaped the opportunities to do what I love every single day. And that’s the feeling I would like to create for each and every one of you out there. ⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣

node.text:
Every outstanding athlete has encountered injuries or physical limitations, every successful business has at one point lost money, and every great student has failed a test.⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
However, every failure should be viewed optimistically. It is now a chance to improve your knowledge gaps to continue to move forward in the future, and is now a problem that you have a better idea of how to solve the next time. ⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
How you deal with failures or adversity will determine the quality of how you will live the rest of your life, so don’t hold yourself back by being consumed by negative energy. The faster you’re able to flip to a positive mindset, the faster you’ll be able to accomplish the task ahead of you. ⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣

node.text:
🚨Grocery Shopping 101🚨
Keep my weekly meal prep simple and grocery shopping quick and affordable. Next time you head out to the grocery store, I recommend to walk the perimeter of the store. That's where you will find your fresh meat, poultry, dairy, eggs, fresh fruits, veggies, healthy carbs from sweet potatoes and fats like avocado. Only go down the middle isles for rice, oats, or nut butter and these can be bought in bulk when you have more time.

Also look what lean cuts of protein are on sale, and look for what the cheapest are per pound. Another good idea is to buy in bulk and freeze any meat you may not want to use that week. Check out what non-starch veggies are on sale. Once you’ve made a list of the items use those foods to fit your macros for the week. No excuses!

Want to know what foods work best for you or how to track your macros properly for your individual goal? I got you covered ✔️💯

🚨 PLEASE READ 🚨
Don’t set out to build the best wall that’s ever been built, set out to lay each individual brick as perfectly as you can. You will notice that with every brick you lay it becomes a bit easier than the last.

If you only focus on the end result you‘ll quickly find yourself feeling overwhelmed way before you even start. What first seemed like an impossible feat on my own journey with each passing day of training (with each brick I laid) the more excited I became and no longer was frightened of the challenge in front of me.

So if I can encourage anyone out there to do something it is to believe in and challenge yourself so that you may feel the exhilaration of victory.

To become a champion, you have to see the big picture. It's not about winning and losing; it's about every day hard work and about thriving on a challenge. It's about embracing the pain that you'll experience at the end of a workout and not being afraid. I think people think too hard and get afraid of a certain challenge. Obviously, if you know me you know that is never how I think, I don’t come up with excuses and don’t think there’s ever been a time or place where it’s too late to shred up!

• KEEP IT SIMPLE •

All too often I see people over complicating both are dieting and training in hopes to see insane results but ultimately fall short. Crash dieting is usually the first course of action that most people take when they think they want to cut some last-minute LB’s but let me be the first to tell you that will only destroy any hard work you put in. Instead of crash dieting either find yourself a coach or educate yourself on how to track your macronutrients to make sure that your calorie count is in line with your goal to shred down.
